### File Structure
```
OnlineAuction/
│
├── app.py
├── templates/
│   ├── dashboard.html
│   ├── auction_catalog.html
│   ├── auction_details.html
│   ├── place_bid.html
│   ├── bid_history.html
│   ├── auction_categories.html
│   ├── winners.html
│   ├── trending_auctions.html
│   └── auction_status.html
│
├── static/
│   ├── css/
│   │   └── styles.css
│   ├── js/
│   │   └── scripts.js
│   └── images/
│       └── (auction item images like watch.jpg, iphone.jpg, etc.)
│
└── data/
    ├── auctions.txt
    ├── categories.txt
    ├── bids.txt
    ├── winners.txt
    ├── bid_history.txt
    ├── items.txt
    └── trending.txt
```

### File Descriptions
- **app.py**  
  The main backend Python application file. It will use a web framework like Flask to handle routing, page rendering, and business logic. This file will manage all nine pages, handle reading and writing to the local text files in the `data/` directory, and implement features such as searching, filtering, placing bids, and updating bid history.

- **templates/**  
  Directory containing HTML template files for each of the nine pages defined in the requirements. Each template corresponds to a page and includes the specified elements with their IDs for frontend rendering and interaction.

  - `dashboard.html` — Auction Dashboard page template.
  - `auction_catalog.html` — Auction Catalog page template with search and filter UI.
  - `auction_details.html` — Auction Details page template showing item info and bid history.
  - `place_bid.html` — Place Bid page template with bid submission form.
  - `bid_history.html` — Bid History page template with bids table and filters.
  - `auction_categories.html` — Auction Categories page template listing categories.
  - `winners.html` — Winners page template showing winning items and filter.
  - `trending_auctions.html` — Trending Auctions page template with ranking and filters.
  - `auction_status.html` — Auction Status page template with status table and controls.

- **static/**  
  Contains static assets used by the web application.

  - `css/styles.css` — Stylesheet for consistent styling across all pages.
  - `js/scripts.js` — JavaScript file for client-side interactivity (e.g., button actions, filtering).
  - `images/` — Folder for auction item images referenced in `auctions.txt`.

- **data/**  
  Directory holding all local text files used for data storage and retrieval as specified in the requirements. The backend will read from and write to these files to maintain auction, bid, category, winner, and trending data.

This structure keeps the backend logic centralized in one Python file (`app.py`) for simplicity, while separating frontend templates and static assets for maintainability and clarity. It fully supports the requirements of the 'OnlineAuction' web application using Python and local text file data management.
